Work Group:     Core
Issue Number:   500
Title:          Can one jump over the definition of a variable of enumeration 
                type?
Section:        6.7 [stmt.dcl] Declaration statement
Status:         active 
Description:
	6.7p3 says:
	"A program that jumps from a point where a local variable with 
	 automatic storage duration is not in scope to a point where it is in
	 scope is ill-formed unless the variable has pointer or arithmetic 
	 type or is an aggregate, and is declared without an initializer." 

	Can one jump over a declaration for a variable of enumeration type?

	Also, since an aggregate can have members with non-trivial constructors,
	using aggregate here is not appropriate.
Resolution:
	Change the sentence above to say: 
	"... the variable has pointer, arithmetic, enumeration, or POD class 
	 type, and is declared without an initializer."
